subSubSection.paragraph:
Type locality: Republic of South Africa : Kwazulu Natal , Caffraria
.

Redescription of adult ( Plate 3 ). Wingspan 18–27mm . Head white, two black spots near posterior edge, two at base of antenna and two by eyes; labial palpus white, but black on joints and at apex; scape white with black ring distally, flagellum whitish ringed grey. Thorax white with four black spots, tegula white with one black spot. Forewing pale grey, paler along fold and subterminally; sometimes a greyish spot in fold before halfway; five irregular longitudinal rows of black spots, fringe pale grey. Hindwing grey, fringe concolorous, a pair of scent brushes near base.
Diagnosis. The paler fold of the forewing is a conspicuous character which usually separates this from other species. The socius of the male genitalia is diagnostic.

Biology. Larvae live in a web on
Gymnosporia senegalensis , Maytenus
or
Cassine
. Adults recorded in every month so probably continuously brooded, subject to local conditions.
Distribution. Republic of South Africa , Swaziland , Mozambique , Zimbabwe , Malawi , D.R.C., Zambia , Kenya , Uganda , Tanzania , South Sudan , Ethiopia , Comoros , Madagascar .
